    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Temperature plays a significant role in the balance between wild yeast and lactobacilli in sourdough starter. Wild yeast is generally more tolerant of warmer temperatures, typically thriving in temperatures between 25°C to 30°C (77°F to 86°F). At these temperatures, wild yeast can produce more carbon dioxide, contributing to the fermentation process and the characteristic sourness of sourdough.\n\nLactobacilli, on the other hand, are more sensitive to temperature and prefer cooler temperatures, typically between 15°C to 20°C (59°F to 68°F). At warmer temperatures, lactobacilli may be suppressed, allowing the wild yeast to dominate the fermentation process. This is why you may notice a more sour flavor when your starter is warmer.\n\nHowever, it's worth noting that lactobacilli can also contribute to the sourness of sourdough, albeit in a different way. They produce lactic acid, which is a key component of sourdough's characteristic flavor. But the ratio of wild yeast to lactobacilli is more important than the temperature itself. A cooler temperature can actually favor the growth of lactobacilli, leading to a more sour flavor.\n\nAs a general rule, a cooler",
